# Dev environment

This project lives on the `/Volumes/JohnDovey` external drive. Environment variables are set by `/Volumes/JohnDovey/source-john-dovey.sh`, auto-sourced from the shell rc whenever the drive is mounted:

- `ANDROID_HOME`/`ANDROID_SDK_ROOT=/Volumes/JohnDovey/Android/Sdk`
- `GRADLE_USER_HOME=/Volumes/JohnDovey/.gradle`
- `JAVA_HOME=/usr/local/opt/openjdk@17/libexec/openjdk.jdk/Contents/Home` (Homebrew openjdk@17)
- `ANDROID_NDK_HOME`/`NDK_HOME`: prefers NDK `26.1.10909125`, falls back to the newest installed NDK otherwise
- **Xcode**: full Xcode lives at `$JOHN_DOVEY/Applications/Xcode.app`. `DEVELOPER_DIR` points at its `Contents/Developer` (no `sudo xcode-select` needed), with DerivedData/Archives redirected onto the volume too. This is what `gomobile bind -target=ios` will use for the iOS phase — no extra Xcode setup should be needed beyond sourcing this script.
- PATH additions: Android `platform-tools`/`emulator`/`tools`/`cmdline-tools/latest/bin`, `$JAVA_HOME/bin`, `$DEVELOPER_DIR/usr/bin`, plus the OpenCode and Kimi Code CLI tools (also homed on the volume — OpenClaw is no longer part of this script, don't assume it).

**Xcode license gotcha**: a freshly-installed Xcode needs its license accepted (`sudo xcodebuild -license`, run by the user themselves — not something to do automatically) before `xcodebuild`/`xcrun` work. Since `DEVELOPER_DIR` now points here whenever this script is sourced, an unaccepted license can make `git` and other tools fail intermittently with an Xcode license error in any shell that sources it. If `git`/builds start failing strangely on this machine, check this first before assuming load/resource issues.

Any build or run script added to this project should `source ~/source-john-dovey.sh --quiet` at the top before invoking Gradle/Android/Xcode tooling, rather than hardcoding SDK/Java/Xcode paths. See also `android-build.mdc` and `volume-storage.mdc`.
